<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09147e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09147e">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09147e"> 147(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Luda aquis <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>mersan<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> deluserat amnis / Bresanu prolis funere nomen habet</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Galway&apos;s Golden Treasury</b> &hellip; O&apos;Flaherty thus quaintly refers to the curious origin of the name in his very readable book, &ldquo;Iar Connaught.&rdquo;; &ldquo;The river of Galway, whose channel is the conveyance of Lough Orbsen for four miles into the sea, slides with some meander windings in a slow and deep stream till it comes near to the town of Galway.&hellip; The right name of the river is Galliv from the oblique whereof Gallive is formed Galway, and Galvia, whereby the town is now denoted. The occasion of the name a very Irish distich which expresses, thus translated: <mark>Luda aquis mersam deluserat amnis Bressalu prolis, funere nomen habet</mark>. This has been translated into &lsquo;Galleamh, daughter of prosperous Bresal, bathed in the full cool stream&rsquo;: where &lsquo;the bright branen&rsquo; was drowned: from her the river Gailleamh is named.&rdquo; <small> <a name="CT15mar24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CT15mar24"><cite title="source">Connacht Tribune</cite></a> (15 March 1924) 6/1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
